As Flannery O'Connor says, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way... you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate." No matter how thoroughly we describe the properties of a literary work, something transcendent remains. I believe ethics shares this same quality. As Wittgenstein says, "It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental." I suggest that this "something," this je ne sais quoi, is the most powerful attribute of art and morality, and that this transcendental nature of ethics and aesthetics provides a connection point between them.

I believe morality and art are so closely related because we experience both most powerfully at a noumenal level, to use a Kantian term. They impact us in a way that can be experienced but not fully explained. This link is even stronger when it comes to the art of literature. As McKean says, "What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is truly unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, like music, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values... Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there."

Today's Germany is seen as a robust power, a unified country with a unique cultural mix stretching from the shadows of the Alps in Munich to the Baltic Sea city of Kiel. This culture is also felt from Cologne on the Rhine, through the heart of Germany to the Saxon city of Dresden on the Elbe. With such a distinctive culture, it is unsurprising that the Germany we know today originates from various sources and tribes.

Germania is the ancestral homeland of the Germans. The origins of the name are highly debated among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed that the name came from a Germanic tribe known as the Tungrians, who were previously known as Germans before crossing the Rhine and fighting the Gauls (Tacitus, 98). Julius Caesar first used the term "Germanus" in his commentary on the Gallic Wars, where he subdued the Gauls and clashed with Germanic tribes that often crossed the Rhine under dubious guises. He borrowed this term from the Gauls themselves to distinguish those he had conquered (the Gauls) from those he had not. While the origin is uncertain, some suggest it referred to a neighbor in the Gaulish language. In the first chapter of his first book on these wars, Julius Caesar notes: "The Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (the Gauls) are continually waging war... They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles." (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC) Others propose the meaning comes from the spear they used in warfare, known as a "ger" (O.E.D, 2010), or perhaps from the Old Irish word "garim," meaning "to shout," suggesting the Germans were loud or noisy. (Names of Germany)

The early Roman historian Tacitus recorded in his AD 98 work "De Origine et situ Germanorum," which detailed the origins of the Germans, that "I should regard (the Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive... Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?" (Tacitus, 98)

And who would leave Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans, at least not yet. They would send their conquests into the lands of Germania for goods and occasionally lead land campaigns, but ultimately they mostly returned to their expansive empire. Thus, as the Germanic tribes emerged in the middle of the first century, they lived on the borders of the Roman Empire and traded their goods taken from the land, and their skills by serving within the ranks of the Roman army. (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17.)

The play "Twelfth Night" suggests that while disguise can be useful for sustaining long-term deception, ultimately, one must abandon this newly adopted facade to avoid losing oneself entirely in the process. A major issue with ending deception is the potential for feeling alienated. Therefore, one must choose between self-preservation and maintaining relationships with others. While some may react neutrally to discovering they've been deceived, others may not take it as lightly and could be offended by the entire charade. The topic of deception in gender role reversal is particularly challenging because it raises many side questions, the most important being: Why? Why does someone feel compelled to reject their identity and adopt a disguise of the opposite gender? In Viola's case, it's clearly a form of self-protection: "I'll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count..." (5.1.247-249) Newly arrived in a foreign land, Viola feels the need to pretend to be a man to protect herself from potential threats. Viola's plan succeeds but also isolates her from the women around her, cutting her off from an essential support system. To complicate matters further, she is so convincing as a man that Olivia mistakes her for Sebastian and falls in love with her. "Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay." (5.1.138) Additionally, she must navigate suppressed romantic feelings with Orsino: "Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me." (5.1.260-261) Although this may seem progressive, "Twelfth Night" might illustrate to modern readers how deception can unveil suppressed emotions, especially in Olivia and Orsino's cases. Some passages hint that these characters might have unspoken desires that Viola/Cesario's presence forces them to confront. For example, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because he appears as a man, or does she secretly have feelings for women? One could argue this is unlikely, as Shakespeare's Olivia seems to parody those who judge others solely on appearance. This is shown by how easily Olivia shifts her affections from Cesario to Sebastian and starts viewing Cesario/Viola as family rather than a romantic interest: "A sister, you are she." (5.1.315)

German colonial rule has been noted by various observers for its brutality, especially regarding the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Naturally, such a vast entity as an entire colonial empire cannot be explained by such a simple description. The German colonial empire was as diverse in its policies and style of governance as it was in geography. Educational provisions across the colonies were similarly varied. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large number of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Cameroon and other colonies were also praised by contemporary authors.

The situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) presented a stark contrast. Unlike East Africa, where the government established state schools and played a significant role in the education of the natives, in South West Africa, the task of educating the natives was almost entirely left to missionary societies that received limited government support. However, the government invested significant resources towards the education of Europeans in the colony, establishing a system of state schools and providing more substantial support and regulation for missionary schools. These educational policies had long-lasting effects on South West Africa, even after German rule. While other German colonies had a significant number of educated and literate Africans, in South West Africa "the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate." Various social, political, and economic factors led to the different experiences in South West Africa. This paper aims to expand the discussion by identifying these factors and paying particular attention to new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities towards native Africans.

There is a wealth of literature specifically dealing with education in the German colonial empire. Most of these sources are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The goal of early works was primarily to describe the characteristics of educational systems in these colonies. Later writings in English expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in the various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies illustrated significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most prominent work explicitly addressing the topic of this paper is Cohen's study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors that account for the differences between them. According to Cohen, the large settler population of South West Africa explains many of the distinctive aspects of the colony's educational system.

Compared to Germany's other colonial possessions, South West Africa had a moderately temperate climate, although much of the territory is covered by arid desert. The European population of South West Africa reflected the relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913, nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

The United States of America and Mexico serve as an example of two nations that were once entangled in a long-standing rivalry that lasted 57 years, from 1836 to 1893 (Diehl and Goerts 2000, p. 145). The pinnacle of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, during which the United States attacked and defeated Mexico, securing Texas and the American Southwest as new territories. Numerous other conflicts occurred between the two nations, finally diminishing just before the First World War. This rivalry began as Americans and Mexicans clashed over key issues such as religion, culture, and tradition, and faced significant conflicts over material interests (Schmitt 1974, pp. 30-31).

This is similar to many other nations that have enduring rivalries with neighbors. Countries that share a border often have conflicts of interest, which lead to rival positions. The United States and Mexico are not unlike many other persistent rivalries between neighboring countries. David M. Pletcher (1977) states, “Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems” (p. 41). Indeed, both nations are geographically close to the United States and have been its rivals, while other Latin American countries have enjoyed and continue to enjoy good relations with the United States.

Religious issues created a divide between the two nations, a problem that has troubled many countries throughout history. Sally Frahm (2001) notes that “if in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy” (p. 86). Similar to the Cold War rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union, this was partly an ideological struggle and partly a competition over interests that each country considered vital. However, in this case, the ideological struggles were not based on political structures but rather on the religious preferences of the United States and Mexico. This distrust stemmed from the historical distrust between the English and Spanish. Inheriting these feelings of distrust from their former colonial rulers posed a significant obstacle to establishing friendly foreign relations between the United States and Mexico.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) list 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States during the 57-year rivalry period. Most of the disputes described by Diehl and Goerts revolved around territorial issues related to border raids from Mexican territory into the United States and other frontier problems. Border raids by bandits and outlaws into American border towns were a major problem until both the United States and Mexico exerted military force on their borders (Schmitt 1974, p. 97).

Schmitt (1974) explains that the rivalry between the two nations began to lessen as “Mexico became clearly dependent on the United States in a substantial way” (p. 109), and ultimately ended as American ambitions “shifted from territorial expansion to economic intervention in Mexico” (p. 110) in the later part of the 19th century.

Fifteen years ago, I was suddenly and unexpectedly disabled by an illness I had never known existed.

At the time, I was a nurse. I chose this profession out of a deep-seated need for the safety and security I lacked as a child. "You'll always be able to find work; people will always get sick," was the mantra I heard repeatedly as I reached adolescence and beyond. So, even though my dream was to become a scientist or a journalist—preferably a bit of both—I chose nursing.

Nonetheless, there I was: 46 years old and single, with no money in the bank and unable to work. To this day, I am still disabled, and after 15 years of living on Social Security Disability, I have literally nothing left that I can call "mine." I get by, but every day is a struggle and an attack on my security, safety, and self-esteem. Nothing in my life is certain anymore, yet there is one thing I know to be true. I could not have managed all these years without the help of my family and a few good friends, no matter how strong I was. And believe me, when real disaster strikes, you do not feel strong at all.

My point is that there will always be emergencies in life—big and small. There are no guarantees, and no matter how well you prepare, some things are just too big to overcome on your own.

I completely agree that we in the U.S. need to stop relying solely on big government; heaven knows it's moldy and falling apart anyway. Yet I would much rather see Americans learning to trust one another again—learning to help each other and ask for help, rather than each of us individually building fallout shelters in the backyard.

The Conservatives in the U.S. talk about the "rugged individualism" that built this country; but in truth, it wasn't rugged individualism that kept our forefathers going in hard times, it was compassion, mutual respect, and the sharing of resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't make it to the coast by going it alone.

So, by all means, be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit; first aid supplies, water purifying tablets, and plastic sheeting and duct tape for the windows in case of a biological attack. I have several flashlights and all sorts of batteries, lots of candles, waterproof matches, and canned goods too. If you have the land and resources for a small farm and the ability to can or preserve your own food—do it. It's a great idea, as is a wood stove, as long as you do not live in an apartment.

But while you're at it, get to know your neighbors.

At some point in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince was born who would later be known as Buddha. Over his lifetime, he renounced worldly life and attained enlightenment, with his teachings giving rise to Buddhism, the most orthodox of which is Theravada Buddhism. This religion is about two and a half thousand years old and has changed since Buddha's time. This is evident in many ways, such as in Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is held. Both monks and laypeople participate in this event, which is religiously significant, even though Buddha never mentioned such celebrations. These differences range from surface-level traditions to the core beliefs of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist community, both from the monastic and lay perspectives, has had to adapt its doctrinal principles over time. This is due to both external and internal influences, whether hostile or benign.

Several terms will be used frequently in this discussion. The concept of internal versus external is key. An internal force comes from members of the Buddhasasana, regardless of monastic status. An external force is any influence from non-Buddhists. A hostile force is one that harms or intends to harm the Buddhist community, arising from a negative view of Buddhism. A benign force neither wishes to harm nor help the Buddhist community, though it may unintentionally do so. These terms will appear repeatedly throughout this discussion.

First, it is crucial to explore the fundamental teachings of the religion—the core doctrines of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem of the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma consists of the Tripitaka—the three baskets—of Buddhist scriptures. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka includes the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka covers the metaphysical aspects of Buddhism. The metaphysical concepts include Anatta—no soul, Dukkha—life's inherent suffering, and Anicca—the impermanence of all things. Only by understanding these concepts can one end Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, which continues endlessly. With the end of Sansara, lobha—desire, dosa—hatred, and moha—delusion will also cease when one becomes enlightened. The Vinaya Pitaka sets forth rules for living. For laypeople, there are five precepts (I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not engage in sexual misconduct, and I shall not consume intoxicants). Monks adhere to many more disciplinary rules. The most fundamental doctrinal concept in Buddhism is that of the four noble truths. First, Dukkha; the truth that life is suffering. Second, that attachment causes suffering. Third, that suffering can be overcome.
