Culture is crucial in any negotiation. It can be defined as much by what it is not as by what it actually is and what it signifies. Culture is neither homogeneous nor a specific entity. It is also not singular or uniform. Statements like "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are accommodating" are inherently broad and overly simplistic. While understanding a culture's generalizations can be appropriate, it is much more productive for a negotiator to understand the culture's significance to the matter at hand and how that culture's attitude can and will affect the negotiations. When one encounters a foreign culture, one experiences it in a way that is relatable to one's own culture, and comparisons naturally arise.

Trying to understand a foreign culture or mindset can involve anything from exploring its history to recognizing its prejudices. Instead of judging or trying to change a culture, one should simply accept it as it is and work within its boundaries, especially in the context of negotiation, and especially if one comes to the table with a weaker bargaining position. Similarly, respect for traditions and beliefs can only help a negotiator on "away" territory to overcome cultural barriers and advance the negotiation.

It is important to note that culture does not necessarily limit itself to a national/international dichotomy. Most companies within a nation establish their own corporate culture. For example, a corporate culture might emphasize long office hours or a more relaxed schedule. Evidence of corporate culture can be seen in employee dress codes, communication style (direct vs. indirect communication, delegation of duties), and hiring practices. Some companies encourage philanthropy at any level from employees, while others restrict it to "company-approved" charities or fundraisers. The differences in American corporate culture from company to company (and indeed, intra-company diversity exists even from region to region, including urban to suburban environments) illustrate the diversity of thought that can exist within a particular societal culture. Certain cultures are not nearly as stratified as American culture and may appear more uniform to an outsider, but a similar exterior is simply a sign to dig deeper.

Values are even more important to understand because they provide the reason behind a culture. If saving face or communal harmony is valued in a culture, it's certain that a negotiator will not publicly shame his company or superior to succeed at the negotiation table. Likewise, a negotiator from a culture that values hard-driven bargains will not necessarily be driven to settle at the earliest opportunity. Considering these generalizations is important before approaching the negotiating table. However, a negotiator is well-advised to learn something about their opponent on a personal level to make the negotiation effective.

"The fool says in his heart, 'There is no God.'" This quotation is first seen in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible and is found at the beginning of St. Anselm's argument about the existence of God. This belief also seems to be held by another author we will discuss, Thomas Aquinas. Since each of their arguments defends the same concept, and our challenge is to determine which is the better of the two, we must, for brevity's sake, start with the assumption that they are both correct in their belief in the existence of God, particularly the God of the Bible. Allowing for a God-like figure that may not resemble the one in whom our two authors believe would not permit us to adequately compare their arguments, as they essentially defend one specific concept of God. That said, I suggest that while each presents valid points, neither truly provides a comprehensive foundation for belief in God. To illustrate this, we will first examine St. Anselm's basic argument. Anselm's passage reflects a path of gaining understanding through faith, looking within oneself to find proof of God. He explains that because God exists in our understanding, we cannot effectively conceive his nonexistence. While this concept, when laid out in his terminology, is a bit tedious and sometimes unclear, the basic idea is that the proof of God lies within one's own mind. St. Anselm suggests that we need not go beyond the confines of our own soul to find truth about God, but that the existence of this being is recognized as true simply by examining what we inherently know to be true within our own minds. Foreign evidence is presumably unnecessary. This concept of accepting that for which there is no irrefutable body of empirical evidence is often referred to in Christian texts as faith. This idea is very different from the one held by Thomas Aquinas. Aquinas suggests instead that the existence of God can be entirely proven through reason and empirical evidence, needing no faith whatsoever. Such an idea would be useful in evangelism, an important element of Christianity, as it would enable the recruitment of new converts without any dependency upon their willingness to accept something that cannot be proven. They could instead be persuaded by logic alone. Thomas elaborates on five different logical arguments supporting the existence of God: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. In each, he essentially demonstrates that the proof of God lies in the logical necessity for God. If you are told that you are missing one puzzle piece and assemble the rest of the puzzle, logic dictates that you can know the features and the existence of the missing piece without having to see it.

Many authors use various methods to convey a specific feeling or attitude to their readers about important subjects. Some techniques are more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald employs many different techniques in his novel The Great Gatsby. Sometimes, Fitzgerald pairs an adjective and a noun that don't usually fit together to create a certain aura around a subject. Other times, he assigns meaning to a symbol and then uses it for the same purpose. Fitzgerald uses this latter technique with many colors, such as gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink. In his novel The Great Gatsby, F. Scott Fitzgerald builds meaning for colors, particularly white/gray and red/pink, to later remind readers of a feeling associated with an important object.

The meaning Fitzgerald develops and uses for white/gray is uniformity, with white being somewhat nicer and higher class, and gray appearing older and faded. Fitzgerald establishes this meaning at the beginning of the novel with constant use of both colors. Daisy and Jordan are constantly "in white"—in fact, everyone is always wearing white: Nick wears "white flannels" to Gatsby's party, Tom wears a "white shirt" when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine is "powdered milky white". The only time people aren't wearing white is when Nick is observing Gatsby's party: "the halls... are gaudy with primary colors". Fitzgerald further defines these colors by coloring many common, insignificant subjects with them: as Nick goes to work, he travels "down the white chasms of lower New York", the names of people at Gatsby's parties are now "gray names" on Nick's timetable, Catherine's apartment is "one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses"—uniformity. He also describes plain or ordinary people or places as white or gray: Jordan and Daisy had a "white girlhood" together, there are "gray cars" and "gray land" in the valley of ashes, the "Italian child" on the train is "gray", and the dog-seller is "a gray old man".

After adding enough meaning to white/gray, Fitzgerald uses them to indicate insignificance or uniformity to specific subjects. This use of colors to show readers something begins with Daisy. After a long time without any significant use of either color, Fitzgerald describes Daisy as "dressed in white" in "a little white roadster"; readers start to see Daisy less as a character, more as a uniform addition, something Gatsby desires and longs for. Fitzgerald employs more of this technique around Daisy to enhance the impression of Daisy being a more uniform addition, for example, there is a "gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar", and she is again in a "white" dress before Tom and Gatsby's encounter.

San Diego County is highly productive in agriculture due to its mild, sunny climate. Common crops include tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There is a significant market for organic, community-supported agricultural food in the San Diego area, with many local organizations having long waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also popular. Many organic farms also offer tours of their agricultural operations as well as access for hiking, birdwatching, and other recreational activities. This type of operation would allow the landowner to benefit from government programs while enhancing the habitat, thus enabling recreational use and creating opportunities for farm tours and other money-making or educational programs. 

In addition to potentially filling a lucrative niche market, the benefits of organic farming often include greater biodiversity among plants and wildlife in the area due to the absence of chemicals in the soil and water. However, organic farming has higher costs in some respects compared to conventional farming. It requires more intensive labor and management to control pests and weeds and to fertilize the soil without chemicals, and losses are often greater than with conventional methods, while a small organic farm also lacks the economies of scale of large operations. Practices not directly related to organic farming but beneficial for wildlife may also incur higher labor costs, such as planting cover crops, strategic grazing rotation, invasive species removal, and active management of plant growth to provide specific conditions like edge habitats or open areas. Therefore, there are many reasons why the landowner in this scenario might seek financial assistance or expertise to maximize both profit and habitat quality. 

The land chosen for this scenario is a parcel near the town of Potrero, in unincorporated San Diego County, California. It consists of 160 acres of chaparral, non-native Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland near the Cleveland National Forest. It is located in the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. The plan is still under review but currently considers over a hundred species of plants and animals. Many are endangered, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, several butterfly species, and the California gnatcatcher; others are declining and may soon be listed, such as burrowing owls.

This area was inhabited by Native Americans for countless centuries and was later settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800s. This piece of land was part of an original homestead patent and was likely used for grazing and/or wood production for many of the intervening decades.

I chose a piece of property from a real estate website and researched available government programs to see what options a small farmer might realistically have for mitigating costs and preserving wildlife-friendly operations. As a model of what someone farming this land might attempt to achieve, I located an organic farm in the same area.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within this bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, to name just a few. Brothers understand each other far more than anyone else with such a connection, and they can only see themselves when looking at their brother. It is in the most critical situations that the true nature of this bond becomes visible, whether good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry great costs. Part of understanding the emotions born from this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and recognize their own reflection in that person, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In actions and the consequences of those actions, their true character is revealed. In "The Scarlet Ibis," two brothers explore this theme and all the raging emotions that accompany it. Through a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys embark on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother survives. The theme is expressed through the direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator's perspective, which conveys the complex feelings of the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which have a significant influence on his actions.

The protagonist's actions can all be summed up by one central emotion: pride. From the first outing with his little brother Doodle to their final, fateful adventure, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He wanted a brother to whom he could teach all his worldly skills, like "…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…" He wanted a brother who could fill the role of "…someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn…" Obviously, these things are impossible given Doodle's condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making it unlikely he would even survive. Even then, it was nearly impossible for him to ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, whose head was filled with wild fantasies, to see all those dreams shattered in an instant. In fact, he is even shown to harbor some anger towards the small child, as he recalls beginning to consider killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? Yet his heart melts when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist such hope! This shows that his conviction probably wasn't very strong. In the back of his mind, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complex, creative information-processing system. As technology progressed from primitive to modern, the metaphors for describing the brain evolved as well. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then a papyrus sheet, later a book, and most recently, a computer. When learning about the brain, it's important to remember that these metaphors have limitations and can lead to incorrect conclusions.

Information processing starts with input from the sensory organs, which convert physical stimuli like touch, heat, sound waves, or light particles into electrochemical signals. The brain's algorithms transform this sensory information repeatedly through both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at an image of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing assembles basic information such as color, orientation, and the borders of the object—where the color changes significantly over a short distance—to determine that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses decisions made at certain stages of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. In this example, top-down processing might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.

Once information is processed to a certain degree, an attention filter evaluates the importance of the signal and decides which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For instance, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might notice your name even in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results are repeatedly modulated by attention.

In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term memory. Initially, information is encoded. Each type of sensory input has specific forms of encoding. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to the appearance of the printed word, phonemically, referring to the sound of the word, or semantically, referring to the meaning of the word. Once stored, information must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for about 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a specific series of neurons for a short time. Information in long-term memory is thought to be maintained in the structure of certain proteins.

There are numerous models of how knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on how humans retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others on neurophysiology. The semantic network model proposes that there are nodes representing concepts, connected based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, "chair" might be linked to "table," which could be linked to "wooden," and so on.

In 2007, the United States of America was engulfed in a severe financial crisis. Unemployment rose, the housing market collapsed, and many of America's largest and most significant corporations were left devastated. This recession continues today, prompting the question: how did this crisis arise, and how can we prevent it? The financial crisis was largely the result of selfish and naïve political decisions that pushed banks and firms to issue subprime loans into an already underdeveloped and inadequate financial infrastructure. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to endorse and repackage these mortgages into CDOs and CDSs. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, banks lacked sufficient capital reserves and passed the chaos onto the repackaged mortgages they had sold, affecting the entire economy.

The roots of the financial crisis trace back to 1999 during the Clinton era, as the President sought a second term in office. He aimed to extend his tenure by boosting his popularity. To achieve this, the Clinton administration relaxed lending restrictions, setting a grim stage for the subprime crisis seven years later. In 1999, Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported: "Fannie Mae, the nation's largest underwriter of home mortgages, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and moderate-income people and felt pressure from shareholders to maintain its phenomenal profit growth." Holmes accurately predicted the potential consequences: "But the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s." As discussed in the introduction and as Holmes foresaw, ill-advised lending was bound to lead to an economic meltdown.

Various factors contributed to the economic downturn, one being the new and complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs) were widely used in the years leading up to the crisis, further entangling more sectors of the economy with the housing market. This led U.S. households and financial markets in general to become overleveraged in the housing market, rendering them extremely vulnerable to even minor price changes.

Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had purchased these mortgage-backed securities suffered. The top five U.S. investment banks collectively reported $4.1 trillion in mortgage debts in 2007, accounting for about 30% of the USA’s GDP. Ultimately, Bear Stearns and Merrill Lynch were sold at exceptionally low prices, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subject to heavy regulation. Fannie and Freddie had $5 trillion in mortgage debt and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition. That part of your story where you spread your little writer's wings and take off, amazing everyone with your magnetic, even magical prose. Or the part where your readers fall asleep and/or hit the "Back" button while cursing your name. Dr. Merlin is known for shouting at her monitor when she finds herself overwhelmed with too much information, and not even in a fun way.

Exposition is not your ally.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," yet Dr. Merlin still finds herself in long passages of text where nothing happens, or worse, too much does. Exposition is the little devil on your shoulder whispering to get the history out of the way to reach the good parts (not to be confused with the devil on the other shoulder urging the author to recount every detail of each character's childhood to the audience).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in straightforward prose. In film, exposition occurs when one character unloads a torrent of information on another, like in "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner." In fiction, it's the author doing the telling.

An example is necessary. As you read a story, you're told that the heroine met her beloved at a certain place and time, that they married in a grand fashion, and that her husband was murdered before her eyes. You wouldn't expect this entire sequence to span two pages, with both he and she getting only two lines of dialogue each. You would expect the author to spend time developing the husband's character, showing through his words and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you would equally expect the heroine to reveal in big and small ways how much his presence changed and enriched her life (especially if the story later states this explicitly). A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally invested in his fate and give you insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts, beliefs, and dreams as reflected through his eyes, and so on. You would mourn his death with her, and in doing so, grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect substance to flesh out the simple storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that substance. (*looks at metaphor, sighs, continues*) Sometimes it's tempting to rush past certain things. Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, now works as the night manager of a gas station, has been married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station one day, and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two newscasts from Columbus, Ohio. The first one, which was live, was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The leading story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio, who had stabbed his wife; her name wasn't mentioned, but his name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his mug shot, and he looked like pure evil. They devoted only about two minutes to this story as it was still developing. The only details they provided were that he had stabbed her multiple times and had been arrested. I think they spent the right amount of time on this story.

The second story was about an early morning shooting of Travis Buyers, 18. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area and was critically injured; there were no arrests made at the time, nor were there any suspects. The SWAT Team was investigating the crime. This story seemed short, and I suspect this might have been because it involved a black man or a black neighborhood. I've noticed (and have for years) that minorities are often overlooked when they are victims of crime. If, for example, a white child or adult is kidnapped or missing or a victim of a crime, the media goes into a frenzy; but if it's a minority person, it’s fortunate if it’s even mentioned.

The next story was about a gunshot hole found in a Med-Flight helicopter. Details were provided about where they thought the incident occurred. It had been determined that a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle had hit the helicopter. Crime-Stoppers are offering a five-thousand-dollar reward for tips that lead to the arrest of the shooter.

The next story was about the rain and thunderstorms predicted for Saturday afternoon. They said the temperatures would remain in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. The segment was a bit short, but they used it as a "teaser" to keep viewers tuned in.

They also reported on a robbery at a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. They said a dark-skinned black man robbed the store, wearing a hoodie sweatshirt. He was reported to be about six feet tall and weigh around one hundred and fifty pounds. I thought they spent an unusual amount of time emphasizing that he was black and how dark his skin was.

Another story was about Rene Rodriguez, a convicted Texas drug kingpin. He had been convicted of conspiring to distribute large amounts of marijuana to Ohio from Texas. One curious thing I noted was that instead of saying he was sentenced to twenty-five years in prison, they said "300" months. I am not sure what the angle was there, whether they thought that sounded harsher or something else. They also mentioned he was Hispanic, which I don't think was really relevant to the story.

An ETF, or exchange-traded fund, is a security designed to track an index, a commodity, or a basket of assets like an index fund, but it is more flexible and trades like a stock on an exchange. An ETF offers the diversification of an index fund and the benefits of owning individual stocks, such as the ability to sell short, buy on margin, and acquire as few as one share in any transaction. Although these benefits are highly attractive, the expense ratios of ETFs are much lower than those of an average mutual fund. Unfortunately, there are some downsides, such as the need to pay a commission for any trade involving ETFs, just as you would for a stock order. Another advantage of ETFs is the wide variety of available funds. Even though these benefits are clearly stated, it is always a good practice for the savvy financial investor to assess whether the stated benefits, like diversification, truly exist and to what extent. For this purpose, we will examine the ETF IHF and compare it against the top 10 holdings that comprise the ETF to determine whether the advantages of owning a single ETF come close to those of owning a diversified portfolio of the ten stocks, and whether there are better configurations of the same stocks that would provide a more optimal Sharpe ratio or higher return.

In order to evaluate the ETF, it would be quite unwieldy to include every holding, so we have decided to include only the top ten holdings, accounting for 63.58% of all the assets in the ETF. Below are the top 10 holdings and their percentage of total assets.

To estimate how well these ten stocks represent the ETF IHF as a whole, we can use the current percentage of assets, normalized to 100%, to calculate the contributions of each stock to a portfolio's Beta and Return if the portfolio were made up entirely of these 10 stocks in the proportion established by the ETF through their holdings. The calculations of Beta and return are included in the chart below.

From the above chart, it is clear that the return of a portfolio containing only the top 10 holdings is 6.11% higher than the ETF, a 16% increase in returns. It is also evident that the Beta of the top ten holdings is 0.12 lower than the ETF as a whole. From the results obtained so far, it appears that a portfolio consisting of just the top 10 holdings could provide a higher return with a lower beta. However, there is a possibility that the means of these two portfolios may not be statistically different from each other.

To determine whether these portfolios are statistically different, the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks is calculated and normalized to 100% in order to compare their accumulated standard deviation to that of the ETF IHF.

Referring back to Figure 17, there was a sharp decline in commuter log submissions during the third month of the project. This was somewhat discouraging, and it's hard to determine why it might have occurred. With the arrival of winter at a New England campus, there is clearly a decrease in people commuting by bike or on foot, which might account for part of the decline. December also signals the end of the fall semester, when everyone is busy completing schoolwork, processing grades, and the like. Filling out the commuter log may have simply fallen off the radar for many. Additionally, December brings the busy holiday season and the resulting month-long break for students and faculty, during which many do not need to come to campus at all. Classes resume for the spring semester in late January, possibly explaining the low number of logs for that month as well. However, this doesn't explain the low number of submissions for February. One could also speculate that any project of this kind has an initial burst of energy and enthusiasm, which may naturally wane. To counter this trend, we introduced the Carpool Challenge Week, a special blitz campaign in March aimed at reinvigorating the initiative, which did lead to an increase in log submissions for that month. Thus, one of the challenges we faced was how to maintain project momentum in the face of a natural decline in engagement, as well as the specific issue of holiday and semester breaks in higher education.

Another challenge for this project (or any alternative commuting project) is the simple fact that people enjoy the freedom, independence, and flexibility of driving their cars, which is deeply embedded in our culture. Therefore, it is crucial to provide incentives for engaging in alternative commuting modes. We distributed numerous prizes in the form of gift certificates to local restaurants, coffee shops, massage therapists, the local independent bookstore, and even some larger national chain stores. However, it would have been interesting to see how some even larger prizes might have affected participation—such as giving away a nice bicycle, hybrid car, or electric car. This could also have helped combat the dip in engagement the project experienced. The nature of the prizes didn't really change throughout the project. If the prizes had increased in value over the course of the project, that might have helped. The gift cards seemed more than adequate at the start of the project, but if we had announced the addition of a couple of bicycles in December, and then a hybrid or electric car in January, it can only be assumed that participation and engagement would have risen instead of decreased.

In exploring the Library of Congress's collection of early Edison films, I chose to watch all the trick films, which numbered fifteen from 1895 to 1901. These films typically use creative editing to create illusions. My film study mainly focused on describing the poetics of most trick films and examining the evolutionary outlier features present in some of the later films. Generally, trick films at the turn of the century are set-bound, composed within a frontal proscenium, feature no camera movement, use long and medium shots, and follow the strict one shot = one film methodology. However, some films at the beginning of the twentieth century dare to break these guidelines by introducing aspects such as multiple shots.

One of the most noticeable aspects common to trick films is their filming on an interior set within the frame of a frontal proscenium. The camera does not move from its proscenium position to follow figures or objects. This composition was very common in early films and drew its roots from theater and, for trick films, vaudeville and magic acts. One limitation inherent in the use of the stage is that figures in trick films generally only move side-to-side and do not walk towards or away from the camera. For example, consider the action in the film Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900). The actors enter from the right side and move back and forth along the horizontal axis. Even as they go out of frame, the camera does not follow them.

The frontal proscenium style of composition also means shots tend to be long shots and, more rarely, medium shots. Close-ups are never used in any of the trick films from the Edison catalog. This borrows from the theater and vaudeville tradition, where the audience would see the entire performance at any given time, framed by the borders of the stage. As in most early films, the actors do not move from the middle ground towards the camera, so close-ups never occur.

In general, most early trick films follow the pattern that one conceptual shot equals a film. This limits the length of most trick films to about a minute or less, depending on the frames per second used. It also limits the dramatic or narrative usage of the trick films; most of them focus on short vaudeville-style tricks, such as magic, disappearing, and switching acts with little story. Note, however, that in a trick film, one conceptual shot in the viewer’s eyes does not actually equal one physical shot. A single "shot" may actually be several joined together to produce the illusion of appearing or disappearing. Look closely at The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), one of the earlier trick films. A more thorough inspection reveals the moment where the physical shot with Mary's severed "head" begins, even though the entire film is conceptually one shot to the viewer.

The traditional "Gothic Novel" is essentially an "oxymoron for 'Old-New'" both in essence and name, as Ian Watt describes in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. The Gothic style has been criticized, praised, accused of lacking true depth, and admired for the 'terrible sublime' it seemed to evoke (Burke). The original "Gothic Novel," Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, utilized ideas from both "ancient and modern" romances to craft the proto-Gothic genre and develop a new literary expression method. Walpole incorporates "old" theatrical elements and 'new' nature mimicry from 'modern' novels to present what he calls "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic genre draws back to medieval Gothic theater, architecture, and traditions. Even at the time of The Castle of Otranto's publication, the word "gothic" was used to describe various peoples, styles, and periods. It was seen as archaic or unsophisticated against "modern" societal and literary "advancements." The blend of the more theatrical "Gothic" and the novel's new format (allowing a more personal view of characters' psychology) is what enables Gothic to endure for such a long time and simultaneously become obsolete yet new to a reader far removed in time from its original writing.

One of the most prominent gothic concepts found in Gothic novels is the idea of chivalry. The medieval concept of chivalry, the process of training a proper knight, is both preserved and transformed in the original Gothic novel, The Castle of Otranto. Chivalry is crucial to Gothic writers because it represents the classic knight—brave, honorable, competent—and the perceived lack of that ideal, which these writers (particularly Walpole) observed in society. Through chivalric concepts and manners, the "gothic past" becomes idealized and romanticized (hinting at Gothic's future evolution into Romantic) and is employed to attempt to improve the present. At the time of writing The Castle of Otranto, Walpole was in the midst of a politically troubled period and was despairing over the potential future. Immersed in politics and (arguably) unfair accusations, he may have begun to think, even if not explicitly, that the supposed morality and inherent "goodness" in people from the Gothic era had somehow been lost in those individuals who comprised 'present' society. This concept is clearly seen in several characters, including Frederic. Before even meeting Frederic, the reader can tell he embodies many chivalric qualities. He is described as:

His description includes many traditionally chivalric images; Frederic is, above all, a prince, he has suffered, been suitably affected by tragedy that he departs, and is currently presumed to have been killed by infidels. The figure of the "gallant and courteous Knight" is, of course, exaggerated, introducing the soon-to-be Gothic trope of excess (66).

Supply chain management involves the process of moving goods from the customer's order through raw materials, supply, production, and distribution to the customer. The term was coined by Keith Oliver, a consultant, in 1982. He described the overall process of planning, implementing, and controlling activities within the supply chain to meet customer needs efficiently. There are six key elements in a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers use these six elements to provide optimal customer service.

Production is the first step and serves as the foundation for the entire supply chain process. It determines when, why, where, and how everything will be produced. Managers need to understand customer desires, which can be assessed by analyzing the market—the main indicator of customer demand. Once managers have evaluated the market and understood customer demand, they are ready to decide what products to produce and in what quantities. After determining what and how much to produce, they must choose the best production location considering volume and quality while ensuring customer satisfaction. Once the production site is decided, managers focus on scheduling workloads and maintaining equipment. Production is a crucial step in the supply chain, where every detail matters. Poor planning can cost the company significant time and money in the long run. For instance, when I worked at Wal-Mart and Target, both companies had specific designs, manuals, and processes for every business aspect. There were set layouts for employee uniforms and receiving shipments from trucks. Well-defined processes help a company operate smoothly without confusion regarding direction and expectations.

The second key element in supply chain management is supply, defined by strategic decisions to determine a facility's core capabilities, with outsourcing partnerships growing from these decisions. A company may have various production divisions for a single product, each with different equipment, workers, and expertise. The manager must decide which division best fits the product processes. Management might also choose to outsource work to other companies to create velocity, which is the ability to provide quality and flexibility while reducing or maintaining low costs.

Victorian novels are known for their meticulous attention to detail and their focus on the aristocracy of the era. Two novels that are considered Victorian but deviate from this tradition are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights. Both novels incorporate elements of mystery and a flair for the bizarre, which is atypical for novels of the time. This strengthens the characters in each work by providing insights into their motives and emotions.

"And now, hosts of bewildering and confusing ideas crowded his mind. He seemed to still be walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were angrily arguing: for the very words they said echoed in his ears; and when he caught his own attention, ... he found that he was talking to them.... Suddenly he recoiled at the sound of firearms; and loud cries and shouts rose into the air; lights flashed before his eyes, and all was noise and tumult, as some unseen hand hurriedly bore him away. Through all these rapid visions, there was an undefined, uneasy awareness of pain that wore him out and tormented him incessantly." (Dickens, 220)

The two novels often utilize this mystery through dream sequences or dreamlike states, although the content and function vary in each specific case. In Oliver Twist, these strange occurrences often reveal insights into Oliver's inner layers, what pains him, and his awareness of the true nature of the happenings around him. When Oliver's shooting is revisited in chapter 28, he vividly relives the shooting as if in a dream while struggling to find help. The passage emphasizes the lack of control Oliver had over the events that unfolded, as well as the dire straits his health had reached, which was strongly present through Oliver's hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit. The shooting overwhelms him; all his senses are numbed as he fails to notice the "unseen hand" that bears him away. He experiences his despair once again, removed from the shock of pain, as the pain is now constant and linked more with fear than surprise. With Oliver being overwhelmed, the question arises of whose will brought about his misfortune, as it was certainly not his own. This shooting reinforces the notion that Oliver has little control over anything, as he cannot even attempt to gain control over the outcome of events, even when his life is in danger. A growing sense of defeat in Oliver is also implied by this passage, as if old Fagin had begun to break him, forcing him to accept this despair, affecting his ability to react. Otherwise, it can be assumed that Oliver would have made some effort, at least for the sake of his own life.

"The day passed - day! There was no day; it was gone as soon as it came - and night came on again; night so long, and yet so short; long in its dreadful silence and short in its fleeting hours.

A few years ago, I worked in an after-school program tutoring elementary-aged students. I did my best to help them in any subject they struggled with, but my strengths were in English and reading. One of the instructors asked me to assist a little boy named Adrian (I believe he was in third or fourth grade), who was having significant trouble reading. It dawned on me that something was amiss; he had the strangest difficulties. Some letters he could pronounce perfectly, others not at all—it was the oddest thing. You see, he was of Latino descent, I was sure of that, but the boy spoke perfect English. We struggled with it until the day I met his mother. I was helping to babysit (for lack of a better term) a few stragglers while the rest of the after-school group was on a field trip when his mother came in. His mother did not speak a word of English, only Spanish. With my very poor Spanish skills (I was just learning), we managed to communicate. But then it hit me like a ton of bricks: Adrian could read well; he just didn't know the English alphabet very well. I don't know if this realization helped him much, but I hope he's doing better now.

I tell this story to address the issue of the language barrier in schools, especially here in California. I also tell it to show that it's not always as obvious as we might think. Even for a child who speaks perfect English, reading can still be a major challenge. I think everyone can agree that this problem exists, so what do we do? In Adrian's case, the solution was quite simple: tutoring in English reading, particularly the alphabet and pronunciations. But for the many children who barely speak English, the solution is much more complex. There is no single answer. The dual language system, mainstream immersion, private tutoring, ESL classes—none of these things alone will solve this problem. The key lies in combining all of them!

First of all, the dual language system is a great idea. Not just for children whose first language is Spanish, but for all children. "Children in two-way bilingual education programs have been found to outperform their peers academically." There is a lot of fear surrounding this idea, that it's a waste of resources and that the majority of children in schools will not benefit from it. But that's false. If we were to apply these sorts of programs as the rule rather than the exception in classrooms, all children would benefit. How do we approach this? Do we require all teachers to be bilingual? No. That would be unreasonable and somewhat unrealistic. However, I do think there is no reason we can't have special aides, tutors, or whatever you want to call them, who are bilingual.

From a young age, most of us are told there is something greater than we are, beyond our understanding. Some of us are sent to Sunday school to learn about it, while others go to the temple or search within themselves for answers. Many of us readily accept the religions passed down by our parents. However, some of us completely reject them, denying there is anything beyond the knowledge in our own egocentric universe. We might adopt one set of values, only to later change our minds for another. Whatever path we choose, we strive to define a part of ourselves through our own unique spiritual perspectives. We look for a light in the darkness to lead us out of the shadows and into the sunshine.

"A cardinal," my father said when I asked him what his favorite bird was. We sat on the front porch of our house, listening to the rain pounding on the tin roof above us while smoking cigarettes together. The gutters directed the rain down, drowning the plants along the porch's edge. He looked out into the rain with a gaze that seemed half searching, half remembering. Over the past few months, he had grown thinner, and his clothes hung limply from his body. His hair had also thinned, sparser than I remembered. He continued to stare into the rain, avoiding eye contact. I felt alone, scared, and unable to talk to my father about how much I would miss him because talking would only make it more real for both of us. I hugged him, sat back down, moved my chair a little closer to his, and joined him in looking out into the falling rain of the June evening.

My father passed away that December, five days after my twenty-second birthday. The chemo and radiation hadn't eased my father's suffering but kept him alive a few months longer than the doctors had projected; I couldn't define the value of him merely suffering longer. What kind of God would do this, I thought to myself. Alone at night, I said no prayers. If God existed, I thought, he had stopped listening to me long ago.

I hadn't wanted to see him transition from this life to another. So I didn't. I couldn't watch the life that created me as it ended. I wanted to remember my father by how he lived, not how he died. Besides, I knew my father better than they did, better than his family did, and knew Dad wouldn't want his only child to be a spectator at his death. I curled up in a ball in my bed for three days and waited for the news.

No one even called me.

John Taylor of Caroline was an early and passionate advocate of Republicanism. Although primarily a farmer, his profession along with his brief political career made him a man known for his commitment and frankness regarding personal freedom and government. His dedication to an agrarian system formed the basis for nearly all his views on government. His efforts to preserve and promote what he considered the most superior of all careers shaped his arguments on sovereignty, constitutionality, and even the judicial system.

John Taylor believed that the United States had a great opportunity to create an ideal system because there was no native tradition to hinder the creators of the government, allowing for the establishment of a system of self-government. He firmly believed in the natural rights of man and that they are all interdependent—meaning if one is denied, they all fail, and the value of those remaining is diminished. Therefore, these rights should be beyond the reach of the government. He claimed that what some called the "state of nature" meant that those with physical strength and malevolent intelligence benefited, but this must not be the way in a civilization.

To create this ideal society, Taylor believed a government must be made that accounts for the inherent good and evil in man. Taylor was very rigid in his views on dualistic morality. He claimed that "since government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human" (Ibid., pg. 167). He defined good principles as those that protect private property, improve agriculture, and discourage capitalism, believing that a government founded on good principles would function equitably regardless of its administration, which would inevitably be led by greed and self-interest. Self-interest, he believed, was man's motivation in all things, but this trait was only considered evil when it led beyond the creation of a society based on the public good to sub-societies living at the expense of others. A good government was necessary to restrain man's natural evil, and even then, it must be under careful observation to avoid the addition of bad principles.

Like many other staunch Republicans of his time, Taylor called for a strict construction of the Constitution. He wanted an extremely limited Federal government, with no more rights or powers than those explicitly stated in the Constitution. He knew that an extensive Federal government was expensive and therefore likely to be despotic. However, he believed that a simple, literal interpretation was dangerous and that without reference to the intent of the writers, such a method could easily become corrupt. Furthermore, he considered the Declaration of Independence the true charter of the United States because it more explicitly describes the country as a group of sovereign states rather than one nation.

Downwards I stared, my mind grasping the sight before me without emotion. Silently and with practiced awareness, I studied it, but refused to relate it to abstract understanding. Thoughts came and went almost faster than I could catch them. My consciousness worked so seamlessly that it felt like I had no real thoughts of my own, only a fluid experience of what I was seeing. Once, upon advice from an artist I worked with, I bought a book called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain". I had wanted to learn to draw since I was six, and this book teaches everything from understanding what a pencil is to the brain processes for interpreting lines. One technique it teaches is to frame any picture the artist wants to study with a square. This turns an overwhelmingly detailed image, like a bowl of fruit on a table in a kitchen connected to a dining room, into something easily grasped—a bowl of fruit on a simple plane. At that moment, staring at the bowl before me, I couldn't mentally project that artist's frame. I was so overwhelmed, so amazed, that I could only stand and gaze in wonder. Picasso went through his blue period, Monet loved greenery, and Italian Renaissance masters displayed a rainbow of colors. If I had any pretensions of seeing my perspective as artistic, then before me were the beginnings of my picture, the start of my story, Work in Brown. Fingertips touched my chosen tool, muscles tightened and relaxed as my hand moved through space, my mind's will taking shape in what could have been my most creative moment. Water swirled, serene and smooth, crystal clear and clean. Flakes of matter broke away and disappeared into nothingness. Muscles tightened, jerked, and spasmed more quickly and anxiously the second time, as my hand struck the toilet handle again. The offensive brown package wouldn't budge, stuck like a slug at the bottom of the toilet. Mop loosely held, feet apart, green tie uncomfortably around my neck, I frowned slightly at the rude bundle of processed animal and plant matter someone had left as a message for the cleaners at Rite Aid. A few more flushes, a few more peaceful, introspective moments to myself, then my hand reached to the wall on my right, grabbed the sheet at the end of the toilet paper, and began wrapping itself until it looked like an oven mitt. Standing upright, then bending at the waist, my hand slowly dipped into the bowl, like a mother reaching into an oven for the Thanksgiving turkey…

Teenagers are dying behind the wheel. Various factors combine to create this deadly vector of statistics for the youngest American drivers. The National Institutes of Health explain that one aspect of the problem is that the teenage brain is literally not prepared for the dangers of driving. Simple inexperience is also at the core of the issue. This inexperience not only leads to more fatal accidents but also to a higher rate of vehicle rollovers, speeding, and driving off the road. Teens also fare much worse when traveling with their peers—which anyone with a bit of sense knows they do regularly. The Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center conducted a study showing the following correlation: between the age of the passenger and the number of traffic accidents occurring. California and other states have attempted to increase the safety of teen drivers by requiring temporary provisional licenses that limit the hours teens may drive and prohibit other minors as passengers. However, provisional driver's licenses are, in my opinion, merely stopgap measures. The real issue is that the youngest drivers, as a group—by all statistical indicators—are simply not able to adequately handle the risks and responsibilities. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman believes even 18 is too young for a regular driver's license. USA Today reports that Zuckerman has conducted research suggesting a widespread desire among those under the age of 19-20 to take risks purely for the thrill. Thus, it makes sense to delay driving at least until the tendency for thrill-seeking begins to subside. If we continue to issue driver's licenses to young teens, we will not only continue to see deadly accidents, but the death toll is likely to reach alarming levels in the next few years. By 2010, the children of the Baby Boomers will be eligible to drive, and millions of new teen drivers will be ready to hit the road. Legislation addressing this issue would be relatively straightforward. Schools could continue to offer driver's education classes to start the learning process for future drivers, but no one under the age of 18 could operate a motor vehicle. A provisional permit could still be issued before granting a full driver's license, and a certain number of practical driver's training hours would also be required. The specific number of required hours could be based on the number of hours already required by most states (in California, for example, that number is currently 6 hours behind the wheel and 50 hours of practice with an adult). Since the deadly statistics for teen drivers come from a cross-section of all states, uniform national legislation on this issue would be a reasonable—and, I believe, effective—means of protecting teens across the nation. The legislation I suggest is by no means a new idea.

This document addresses three aspects of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). Initially, it provides a brief definition of the disorder. Next, it explains the diagnosis, highlighting common characteristics or "red flags." Finally, the document concludes with strategies for how a teacher in a mainstream classroom can support a student with CAPD.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), also known as Auditory Processing Disorder (APD), "refers to the efficiency and effectiveness with which the central nervous system (CNS) uses auditory information. Narrowly defined, (C)AP refers to the perceptual processing of auditory information in the CNS and the neurobiological activity that underlies this processing and results in electrophysiological auditory potentials" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This means it is a disorder where the central nervous system (i.e., the brain) cannot properly process what is heard. People with CAPD have normal hearing and are thus not considered "hearing impaired"; rather, the brain area responsible for interpreting sounds, distinguishing words, or separating conversations from background noise does not function typically.

The earliest mention of what became known as CAPD dates back to the mid-1950s, referred to as "auditory imperception" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005), when researchers were studying children with communication disorders. The Italian research team of Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari began developing tests for these children in 1954; in 1961, Kimura "introduced dichotic testing and formulated a model to explain the physiology of the CANS underlying dichotic perception" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). A national conference in 1977 stimulated research into children with CAPD.

CAPD manifests in various ways: the affected individual may struggle to localize or hear sound in space; may find it difficult to distinguish between two or more "acoustic events" (sound occurrences); may be unable to recognize sound patterns; may fail to differentiate changes in speech (such as detecting sarcasm via a change in tone); one sound might be masked by a subsequent sound; may lack the ability to synthesize auditory clues (interpreting them meaningfully for action); and may be unable to determine the sequence in which auditory information is presented (Ferre).

To diagnose CAPD, the patient must undergo "systematic observation of listening behavior and/or performance on tests of auditory function," which can be conducted by "audiologists, SLPs, psychologists, and others using various measures to evaluate auditory-related skills" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This may include questionnaires and surveys, observation of auditory behaviors, and how the patient responds to specific stimuli. Currently, there is no single tool or test consistently used with a high rate of diagnostic success, and the disorder's cause is unknown. Many tests present the patient with multiple, simultaneous auditory stimuli and require differentiation of certain items, like a series of words or numbers. More advanced tests involve recording acoustic signals within the ear and measuring responses to these signals.

In my pursuit of an education in social work, I aim to follow a career with the Division of Family and Children Services to assist children who have been abused or neglected, and to offer support to struggling families. The values I can bring to the field of social work include service, respect, ethical behavior, commitment to enhancing relationships between people, and continuous professional development to maintain competence in my field. These core values are not just crucial for social workers; they hold personal importance for me.

I've always wanted to help others but was unsure of the career path I wanted to take. During my high school and college years, I witnessed many people deny their problems, and some used coping mechanisms that were less than ideal. Because of these situations, I decided to pursue a Bachelor's degree in Psychology. Still uncertain about a career path, I took a break after graduating from Piedmont College in 2009. One summer day, I visited a friend who introduced me to a sixteen-year-old boy sitting nervously on her couch. She explained that he was there to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I learned he had called the police to his parents' house. To see if I could help, I drove to his parents' home. Once there, I privately shared my concerns with the police and mentioned that I had just graduated with a degree in Psychology from Piedmont College. The police asked me to speak with the parents since the law couldn't help the teenager. When I questioned the parents about the situation, they seemed uneasy and made excuses, describing their son's "manipulative" behavior in involving outsiders to settle "simple" disputes. After this particular experience, I began to seriously consider a career in social work to help children with "simple" disputes among family members.

Another value essential for the field of social work is social justice. As a society, we claim the individual is important and mourn those we have lost. Yet, the concept of the "individual" in society often aligns more with archaic traditions than true uniqueness. If society mourns lost individuals, why do we strive to be like "everyone else?" I am an individual and do not enjoy limiting myself to be similar to others. Throughout my high school and college years, I protested against social injustice whenever possible: coloring my hair in unnatural shades, wearing clothes that matched my personality, piercing my ears beyond the traditional set, declaring my involvement with GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), and fighting against racism and discrimination whenever I encountered it, etc. I believe in social justice and will continue to stand against social injustice.

The paper discusses the biological and sociocultural models related to the sleep disorder insomnia. The biological model centers on inherited genetic information and medical health aspects. The sociocultural models explore environmental relationships and their relevance to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. This review of insomnia examines these models and explains each selected research that relates to and clarifies these models. The research explanations and findings are then critiqued to highlight their specific strengths and weaknesses.

A sleep disorder can be classified as a primary sleep disorder, a sleep disorder related to another mental disorder, or a sleep disorder linked to other issues. Primary sleep disorders include Dyssomnias or Parasomnias, whereas those related to another mental disorder are associated with an Axis I or Axis II disorder. Other sleep disorder categories may result from medical complications or substance intake. Dyssomnias include: Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing-Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). Primary Insomnia represents a complication in achieving or maintaining adequate sleep, while Primary Hypersomnia involves difficulty in staying awake, both lasting at least one month. Narcolepsy includes cataplexy and/or automatic REM sleep. While Dyssomnias focus on initiating and maintaining sleep, Parasomnias are related to behavioral abnormalities and/or physiological occurrences during sleep. Parasomnias include Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. Sleep disorders related to another mental disorder involve sleep difficulties associated with Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Mental Retardation). This review primarily focuses on insomnia and to some extent on primary sleep disorders concerning biological and sociocultural models.

The biological model of sleep disorders emphasizes genes, heritable factors, and physiologically acquired aspects of sleep disorders. Neurons in the hypothalamus containing orexin are responsible for regulating sleep and wakefulness. This study conducted experiments with mice and found phenotypic GABAB receptors on orexin neurons responsible specifically for sleep/wake states. Activation of the GABAA receptor induces responses that promote sleep. If prevented from firing, it can reduce anxiety and promote sleep. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) increased sleep time (Matsuki et al., 2009). Such results suggest that mouse models can be generalized to human studies. This indicates a genetic and environmental basis for the physical GABAB receptor in humans. A problem or absence of this receptor could impair the ability to have adequate sleep without medication. The sociocultural implication is that if the phenotype is inherited, it could regulate sleep, and receptor alteration would naturally disrupt an individual's sleep. This negatively impacts aspects of life such as school, career, and daily events involving monotonous tasks and focus.

I have been a student at University Park for about two and a half years, or four and a half semesters. For many, including myself, navigating campus can be challenging. My freshman year, I lived in a dorm room in East Halls, almost the easternmost point of campus, not counting the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Walking from Stuart Hall to classes in far-off places like the Willard building, near the center of campus, could take up to 25 minutes, especially in bad weather, which is common in State College. An alum not much older than me told me that not long ago, East Halls dorms were separated from the rest of the campus by vast areas of unused land. Now, that space is filled with sports fields, large new buildings like the new Creamery and health services building, and is surrounded by apartments. As our campus continues to grow, moving from place to place becomes increasingly difficult. What's the best solution to the mobility problem? On a college campus, it's the bicycle. But a bike alone won't solve anything. Students need to ride them, and the campus must be designed to accommodate cyclists' needs.

I spoke with a friend who recently got back into cycling after a break of several years. He mentioned that he wondered why he ever stopped. "Bikes are great," he said, "for a few years it wasn't cool to ride a bike, but it’s the only way to get around." Besides being good for your body, cycling is the most efficient way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and a bit of physical effort can take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now live off campus, just as far from the campus center as some dorms. The smartest decision I've made this year was to buy a bike. Every day, I have classes in the Thomas building, which is a twenty-five-minute walk from my home. Riding a bike can cut that time to 5 minutes if I pedal fast enough. The only issue is that Pollock Road is the most direct route to the Thomas building from my house, and it's not always easy to travel, bike or no bike. Walking has its merits too, but personally, I'm too busy to walk. Without my bike, walking would be my only reliable way to get to class. Walking to Thomas every day would take an extra 30-40 minutes out of my day. That's more than two and a half hours every week. Add to that all the other time I would need to walk to and from other classes, appointments, etc. That's more time than I can spare.

Aldous Huxley criticizes the looming threat of technology and the capitalist structure that reinforces it through the creation of a dystopia in his novel "Brave New World." People value community over the individual and are conditioned from the start to seek immediate happiness above all else. The citizens are revealed to be mere pawns in a larger game, bound to a single ideology dictated by the World Controller. When examining the work through the lens of Marxist theism, one notices the author's underlying concerns about the development of these systems. Frequent Marxist terms like homogeneity and reification reinforce the idea that Huxley's novel is a commentary on the flaws in the emerging economy of his time.

Capitalism is satirized through the Marxist concept of false consciousness. Essentially, the common people are prevented from understanding their true economic relationships with other classes, as they are primarily interested in their own gain. This is said to be the result of ideological control over the proletariat and ordinary workers, something clearly evident in the conditioning of people in "Brave New World." The common classes, such as Deltas and Gammas, lack true will of their own; through hypnopaedia, the drive to consume, spend, and indulge is strengthened above all else. As previously stated, this is manipulated by the World Controller. Hegemony, the idea that groups of social classes are completely dominated by a separate group of individuals, is clearly used in this case. The lower classes are entirely unaware of the manipulation, quite literally "buying into an ideology that supports that structure" (i.e., capitalism and consumerism). The upper classes are born with the ability to be aware of it but do nothing; few Alphas or Betas, aside from characters like Bernard, do more than simply accept their place. Indeed, the interactions of the social classes, as discussed in greater detail, are significant indicators of the perceived oppression by capitalism.

Relationships between disparate individuals do not exist in "Brave New World." The novel seemingly refuses to distinguish the characters—they are, even among the main ones, lacking in depth. Perhaps Huxley suggests that the rise of technology and capitalism together deprives humanity of free will and expression. Love does not exist, nor do the extremes of any single emotion; instead, interactions are kept superficial, distinctly portrayed through the men's remarks about women primarily focusing on their physical appearance (e.g., pneumatic quality), and the women's unabashed comments about their encounters. Furthermore, each societal class's complacency with their status in the hierarchy indicates the socioeconomic effect of capitalism. Their absolute obedience to their role in the community reflects Marxist thoughts on the proletariat, who are falsely assured of their own superiority over everything else as long as they continue to consume, obey, and stay in line with the rest of their peers.

Nearly four years ago, I attended a course on Islam at CBC. One of the key topics of intense debate in the class was whether Islam is a hostile religion. I think this question is even more pertinent today than ever before. Reflecting on events since 9/11, I have personally observed the mass media shift from a hostile perspective of Islam and its extremists to an extreme form of tolerance for Islam in America. I don't think in 2001 we could have had a presidential candidate named Borac Obama, who has an evident Muslim background in his family.

The biography of the Prophet is intriguing to me because, according to what I know of Muhammad's history, the biography contradicts his personality. From what I have known and learned in the past, I thought Muhammad forced conversions to Islam. He would conquer and take over tribes and then compel them to adopt the Islamic faith. But according to the biography, Muhammad is portrayed as a kind of martyr who was misunderstood and even humbled himself before others. After this, people gradually saw the 'truth' in his teachings and sought him out.

Additionally, there are some striking similarities between the ministries of Jesus and the 'miracles' of Muhammad. The most evident is when he took mutton and milk and multiplied them so there was more than enough for forty men. This style of writing leads me to believe the authors wanted Muhammad to be seen as the humble prophet who didn't need to prove anything but simply lived in truth and miracles. This type of misconception is the worst because it diminishes the miracle and life of Jesus Christ. To me, it feels like they are attempting to appropriate the life and identity of Jesus through Muhammad.

There are also many stories in the biography that make it seem like part of their agenda is to provide proof of 'witness' or how people 'on their own' converted to Islam. But the issue is that many of the stories come from at least a third-party perspective. In the stories, the author illustrates that they heard from someone who heard from someone else, and so on. I didn't like this much because, although their idea was to provide proof of the truth of these stories, I felt it diminished them and made them seem even more suspicious.

I think what bothers me most about this work is that they try to exalt Muhammad as a godly man who was humble, endearing, wise, and gentle. But history contradicts the notion that Muhammad was a gentle and humble man, and I can't help but wonder if Muslims today know the true history behind Muhammad's rise to power.

The teachings of Jesus and the beliefs he held during his life were left behind as Christian thought evolved after his time. Looking at this history broadly, we notice a trend of Christianity moving further from its origins. Today's world shows a growing awareness and an unprecedented progressive tendency. Although traditional individuals remain and resist thinking beyond what they were taught, this segment may not have enough influence over the whole. Among Christians, historical awareness is set to grow immensely in the coming years. A desire will spread to differentiate doctrines added to Christianity over time from the original intentions of the religion's namesake. It might take decades or centuries, but the result is inevitable: a significant reversal in Christian history will occur. There will be a shift back to its original form. A movement will grow to peel away layers of doctrine, one by one, as if the clock were turning back, until only the essence of what Jesus introduced to humanity on behalf of God remains, before any other thinkers made claims. As this trend moves through the United States and Europe, influencing many to worship as if they lived in Jesus' time, following only his ideas, the church as an institution will remain strong to lead the way. However, as the theological clock moves backward, the vast diversity in Christendom will transform into more uniformity in belief and practice. Across regions, denominations, and divisions of all kinds, we will see increasing similarities instead of differences. Human history is filled with notable reversals. An example is how Christians were once persecuted by the Roman Empire, which later became a Christian institution. Our country has moved from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The significant reversal in our future will unfold in the realm of the Christian religion, undoing history in search of the source, and reducing diversity in the process. It is crucial to note that a part of what will make this possible is interpreting Jesus’ words metaphorically, not as literal statements. So what has happened since Jesus' time? Looking far back in history, we find Judaism, the theological start for Christianity. Monotheism, the perception of a divinely revealed religion, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures were central to the religion by the time Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish population didn't share a single spirit. They were divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and a large majority of common people.

I believe that "The Jungle" demonstrates how deep down, humans are inherently greedy and selfish. They only care about themselves and making their lives as good as possible, never looking out for those beneath them. "The Jungle" illustrates this in many ways. The most obvious example is the owners and managers of large factories. All they want is to make their companies and factories as large and successful as possible. They don't care about anyone or anything that gets in their way or is harmed by their progress. According to Upton Sinclair's work, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." Sinclair tries to depict the great damage this pollution causes. He shows that the owners are indifferent to any people or animals that might get hurt. They are unconcerned about the huge plumes of smoke billowing from the factories or the runoff of animal waste from the thousands of pens around Packingtown.  
The owners and managers also didn't care about their employees, who were making them rich. They would do anything to make or save an extra buck, "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar." They forced their employees to work terrible hours, and without even a day's notice, they might lay off large numbers of people at once without any compensation or help finding a job. During the era in which "The Jungle" is set, there were few, if any, laws or regulations protecting workers' safety or well-being. This allowed managers and owners to act without restraint, forcing their employees to speed up progress and work in dreadful conditions. Although the book never directly states it, the people who lived and worked themselves to death in Packingtown were simply expected to endure the horrible conditions both while working in the factories and living nearby. There were no agencies or organizations to provide information or assistance to the workers. There were unions that were formed, but they often did more harm than good as they profited from the poor workers. The workers were treated so poorly and had no way to escape the system of Packingtown that they were described as slaves: "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

Dream-land is considered one of Edgar Allan Poe's self-proclaimed best poems. In "Dream-Land," Poe uses the term "Thule" in lines 6 and 56, which Mabbott traces back to Virgil. Virgil used the term to refer to an island north of Britain, which the Greeks viewed as the edge of the known world. It is certain that Virgil did use the term, but there is a more recent source deserving some credit. Poe was very interested in German authors. This quote is important as it shows Poe’s familiarity with Goethe’s writing. Karl J. Arndt, in his book "Poe’s Politian and Goethe’s Mignon," comments on the similarity of their two poems, concluding that Poe was imitating Goethe.

The Oxford Companion to English Literature notes that Goethe was a celebrated writer of the poetic drama Faust, published in two parts, the first in 1808 and the second in the year of Goethe’s death, 1832. Within the poetic verse of the second part of Faust lies a short poem titled "The King of Thule." The poem tells of a king whose wife dies after giving him the gift of a goblet. After her death, he begins to drink heavily and mourns the memory of his deceased queen. He then decides it is his time to die and gives his possessions to his children, except for the goblet. He walks to a cliff, throws the goblet into the sea, closes his eyes, and dies. The demeanor of the King of Thule and the description of the king in Dream-Land are very similar, perhaps a dark reflection of Poe’s loss and reliance on drinking. Faust was also adapted into a romantic drama by H. P. Grattan in 1842, less than a year before Poe used the term Thule in "The Pit and the Pendulum."

Poe references Thule twice in his collected writings. Once, Poe mentions "ultima Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum," but he uses this phrase twice in "Dream-Land," as bookends for the poem. "The King of Thule" and "Dream-Land" can be read as companion pieces. In "Dream-Land," the speaker describes the landscape of Thule as dark and lonely, haunted by dead friends, and sees a shadowed world without color. All of these scenes would be interpreted in Goethe’s "The King of Thule" as he has just lost his wife, is lonely, and has lost his will to rule or even live.
